{
  "question": "Why do wetlands reduce floods and mitigate climate change?",
  "text": "Wetlands reduce floods because they temporarily store rainfall and river overflow; vegetation and shallow basins slow runoff, lower downstream flood peaks, and reduce erosion. [1]\n\nWetlands help mitigate climate change because plants capture atmospheric carbon and waterlogged soils can preserve organic matter for long periods; peatlands hold especially large carbon stores. Protecting wetlands can also avoid carbon-dioxide emissions that may occur when drainage exposes stored material to oxygen. [2]\n\nClimate benefits involve tradeoffs: some wetlands emit methane, and the net mitigation value of protection or restoration depends on the full greenhouse-gas balance, wetland type, condition, and watershed context. [3]",
